# 1Password env-file template — `op run --env-file=.env.op -- <cmd>` resolves
# the op:// references to actual secret values and injects them as env vars for
# the wrapped command. The values never appear in shell scrollback, history, or
# the terminal session of the operator invoking `op run`.
#
# This file is committed (it contains references, not secrets). Anyone with read
# access to the referenced 1Password items gets the values; anyone without gets
# `op` errors and nothing leaks.
#
# Note on the two Spaces credentials (see README "Why two Spaces keys"):
#   - do_token + github_token come from the AgenticOS Infra item.
#   - The spaces_bootstrap_* "plumbing" key comes from GoldberryGrove Infra.
#     AgenticOS and Grove share ONE DigitalOcean account (team MoonBear), so the
#     existing account-wide plumbing key is reused for provider auth. It is
#     operator-only and never surfaced to CI; the bucket-scoped agenticos-tfstate
#     key that this module CREATES is what CI/the root backend consume.
#   - spaces_bootstrap_secret_key's 1Password field label has a trailing space,
#     so it is referenced by field id (f6upwbtfs7jo7f4avwe6kivcwu), not label.

TF_VAR_do_token=op://Goldberry Grove - Admin/AgenticOS Infra/do_token
TF_VAR_github_token=op://Goldberry Grove - Admin/AgenticOS Infra/github_token
TF_VAR_spaces_bootstrap_access_key_id=op://Goldberry Grove - Admin/GoldberryGrove Infra/spaces_bootstrap_access_key_id
TF_VAR_spaces_bootstrap_secret_key=op://Goldberry Grove - Admin/GoldberryGrove Infra/f6upwbtfs7jo7f4avwe6kivcwu
